1 AN ACT concerning minors; relating to the revised Kansas code for care
2 of children; requiring that a permanency hearing for a child in custody
3 of the secretary be held within nine months of such child's removal
4 from such child's home; amending K.S.A. 2024 Supp. 38-2264 and
5 repealing the existing section.
6
7 Be it enacted by the Legislature of the State of Kansas:
8 Section 1. K.S.A. 2024 Supp. 38-2264 is hereby amended to read as
9 follows: 38-2264. (a) A permanency hearing is a proceeding conducted by
10 the court or by a citizen review board for the purpose of determining
11 progress toward accomplishment of a permanency plan as established by
12 K.S.A. 38-2263, and amendments thereto.
13 (b) The court or a citizen review board shall hear and the court shall
14 determine whether and, if applicable, when the child will be:
15 (1) Reintegrated with the child's parents;
16 (2) placed for adoption;
17 (3) placed with a permanent custodian;
18 (4) if the child is 16 years of age or older, placed with a SOUL family
19 legal permanency custodian; or
20 (5) if the child is 16 years of age or older and the secretary has
21 documented compelling reasons why it would not be in the child's best
22 interests for a placement in one of the placements pursuant to paragraphs
23 (1) through (4), placed in another planned permanent living arrangement.
24 (c) At each permanency hearing, the court shall:
25 (1) Enter a finding as to whether reasonable efforts have been made
26 by appropriate public or private agencies to rehabilitate the family and
27 achieve the permanency goal in place at the time of the hearing;
28 (2) enter a finding as to whether the reasonable and prudent parenting
29 standard has been met and whether the child has regular, ongoing
30 opportunities to engage in age or developmentally appropriate activities.
31 The secretary shall report to the court the steps the secretary is taking to
32 ensure that the child's foster family home or child care institution is
33 following the reasonable and prudent parenting standard and that the child
34 has regular, ongoing opportunities to engage in age or developmentally
35 appropriate activities, including consultation with the child in an age-

