1 appropriate manner about the opportunities of the child to participate in the
2 activities; and
3 (3) if the child is 14 years of age or older, document the efforts made
4 by the secretary to help the child prepare for the transition from custody to
5 a successful adulthood. The secretary shall report to the court the programs
6 and services that are being provided to the child that will help the child
7 prepare for the transition from custody to a successful adulthood.
8 (d) The requirements of this subsection shall apply only if the
9 permanency goal in place at the time of the hearing is another planned
10 permanent living arrangement as described in subsection (b)(5). At each
11 permanency hearing held with respect to the child, in addition to the
12 requirements of subsection (c), the court shall:
13 (1) Ask the child, if the child is able, by attendance at the hearing or
14 by report to the court, about the desired permanency outcome for the child;
15 (2) document the intensive, ongoing and, as of the date of the hearing,
16 unsuccessful permanency efforts made by the secretary to return the child
17 home or secure a placement for the child with a fit and willing relative, a
18 legal custodian or guardian or an adoptive parent. The secretary shall
19 report to the court the intensive, ongoing and, as of the date of the hearing,
20 unsuccessful efforts made by the secretary to return the child home or
21 secure a placement for the child with a fit and willing relative, a legal
22 custodian or guardian or an adoptive parent, including efforts that utilize
23 search technology, including social media, to find biological family
24 members of the children; and
25 (3) make a judicial determination explaining why, as of the date of
26 the hearing, another planned permanent living arrangement is the best
27 permanency plan for the child and provide compelling reasons why it
28 continues to not be in the best interests of the child to return home, be
29 placed for adoption, be placed with a legal custodian or guardian or be
30 placed with a fit and willing relative.
31 (e) The requirements of this subsection shall apply only if the child is
32 placed in a qualified residential treatment program at the time of the
33 permanency hearing. At each permanency hearing held with respect to the
34 child, in addition to the requirements of subsection (c), the court shall
35 document:
36 (1) That the ongoing assessment of the strengths and needs of the
37 child continues to support the determination that the needs of the child
38 cannot be met through placement in a foster family home, that the
39 placement in a qualified residential treatment program provides the most
40 effective and appropriate level of care for the child in the least restrictive
41 environment, and that the placement is consistent with the short-term and
42 long-term goals for the child, as specified in the permanency plan for the
43 child;

