1 (2) the specific treatment or service needs that will be met for the
2 child in the placement and the length of time the child is expected to need
3 the treatment or services; and
4 (3) the efforts made by the secretary to prepare the child to return
5 home or to be placed with a fit and willing relative, a legal custodian or
6 guardian, or an adoptive parent, or in a foster family home.
7 (f) A permanency hearing shall be held within 12 nine months of the
8 date the court authorized the child's removal from the home and not less
9 frequently than every 12 nine months thereafter. If the court makes a
10 finding that the requirements of subsection (c)(1) or (2) have not been met,
11 a subsequent permanency hearing shall be held no not later than 60 days
12 following the finding.
13 (g) If the court determines at any time other than during a
14 permanency hearing that reintegration may not be a viable alternative for
15 the child, a permanency hearing shall be held not later than 30 days
16 following that determination.
17 (h) When the court finds that reintegration continues to be a viable
18 alternative, the court shall determine whether and, if applicable, when the
19 child will be returned to the parent. The court may rescind any of its prior
20 dispositional orders and enter any dispositional order authorized by this
21 code or may order that a new plan for the reintegration be prepared and
22 submitted to the court. If reintegration cannot be accomplished as
23 approved by the court, the court shall be informed and shall schedule a
24 hearing pursuant to this section. No such hearing is required when the
25 parents voluntarily relinquish parental rights or consent to appointment of
26 a permanent custodian or a SOUL family legal permanency custodian.
27 (i) If the court finds reintegration is no longer a viable alternative, the
28 court shall consider whether: (1) The child is in a stable placement with a
29 relative; (2) services set out in the case plan necessary for the safe return
30 of the child have been made available to the parent with whom
31 reintegration is planned; or (3) compelling reasons are documented in the
32 case plan to support a finding that neither adoption nor appointment of a
33 permanent custodian are in the child's best interest. If reintegration is not a
34 viable alternative and either adoption or appointment of a permanent
35 custodian might be in the best interests of the child, the county or district
36 attorney or the county or district attorney's designee shall file a motion to
37 terminate parental rights or a motion to appoint a permanent custodian
38 within 30 days and the court shall set a hearing on such motion within 90
39 days of the filing of such motion.
40 (j) If the court enters an order terminating parental rights to a child, or
41 an agency has accepted a relinquishment pursuant to K.S.A. 59-2124, and
42 amendments thereto, the requirements for permanency hearings shall
43 continue until an adoption or appointment of a permanent custodian or a

