1 SOUL family legal permanency custodian has been accomplished and
2 court jurisdiction has been terminated. If the court determines that
3 reasonable efforts or progress have not been made toward finding an
4 adoptive placement or appointment of a permanent custodian or a SOUL
5 family legal permanency custodian or placement with a fit and willing
6 relative, the court may rescind its prior orders and make others regarding
7 custody and adoption that are appropriate under the circumstances.
8 Reports of a proposed adoptive placement need not contain the identity of
9 the proposed adoptive parents.
10 (k) If permanency with one parent has been achieved without the
11 termination of the other parent's rights, the court may, prior to dismissing
12 the case, enter child custody orders, including residency and parenting
13 time that the court determines to be in the best interests of the child. The
14 court shall complete a parenting plan pursuant to K.S.A. 23-3213, and
15 amendments thereto.
16 (1) Before entering a custody order under this subsection, the court
17 shall inquire whether a custody order has been entered or is pending in a
18 civil custody case by a court of competent jurisdiction within the state of
19 Kansas.
20 (2) If a civil custody case has been filed or is pending, a certified
21 copy of the custody, residency and parenting time orders shall be filed in
22 the civil custody case. The court in the civil custody case may, after
23 consultation with the court in the child in need of care case, enter an order
24 declaring that the custody order in the child in need of care case shall
25 become the custody order in the civil custody case.
26 (3) A district court, on its own motion or upon the motion of any
27 party, may order the consolidation of the child in need of care case with
28 any open civil custody case involving the child and both of the child's
29 parents. Custody, residency and parenting time orders entered in
30 consolidated child in need of care and civil custody cases take precedence
31 over any previous orders affecting both parents and the child that were
32 entered in the civil custody case regarding the same or related issues.
33 Following entry of a custody order in a consolidated case, the court shall
34 dismiss the child in need of care case and, if necessary, return the civil
35 custody case to the original court having jurisdiction over the case.
36 (4) If no civil custody case has been filed, the court may direct the
37 parties to file a civil custody case and to file the custody orders from the
38 child in need of care case in that case. Costs of the civil custody case may
39 be assessed to the parties.
40 (5) Nothing in this subsection shall operate to expand access to
41 information that is confidential under K.S.A. 38-2209, and amendments
42 thereto, and the confidentiality of such information shall be preserved in
43 all filings in a civil custody case.

